  "text": "In our study, Coagulase-negative Staphylococcus spp. were the most commonly grown contaminants, organisms which have been increasingly documented as a cause of surgical-site and deep infection. It is now the commonest cause of joint infection in knee replacement surgery 9,10 and a common cause of infection in knee arthroscopy. [CITATION_1] There are cleaning recommendations available from tourniquet manufacturers which state that cuffs can be brushed with mild soap suds and rinsed with warm water. In addition, it is possible to wash them at 60ºC with commercial soap suds in a washing machine. However, they should not be spun dry. After cleaning, the fabric cuffs can be disinfected with alcohol wipes.",
